ownedComment.body: This concerns the determination whether someone has limitations (is compromised) concerning the self care of bathing or in other words, whether someone has the ability to bathe himself. This concerns the washing and drying one's whole body, or body parts (hands, feet, face, hairs). The method of bathing; on bed using a bowl, bathing or showering or washing at the sink. Means; using water and appropriate cleaning and drying materials. Excluding: caring for body parts and toileting. (ICF, NANDA).

properties.documentation: The data collection of one of the self care abilities of the client<sup>1</sup>, specific the ability to bathe one self. The data collection is done by observing particularly the physical appearance and condition of the client and the extent to which the client can take care of his body and appearance (Sesink et.al., 2006). ------------------------- <sup>1</sup> Client, patient, care taker

The hygiene of the body is found important in all cultures. The bathing of the body is an essential part of the hygiene that is taught during the early childhood. Bathing as an activity is conducted independently and in their own responsibility. In case of illness or disability this independency is not always obvious. All sorts of assistive devices help a person to stay independent as long as possible. Think of brackets in the bathroom, shower chair etc. There for the collection of data on self care ability of a client is important. For the client and the nurse / care provider the physical hygiene is an important part of the day (Transferpunt Vaardigheidsonderwijs, 1994). The nurses data collection is the knowingly, systematic and purposeful collection of data, and accordingly organize them in a preconceived plan (Gordon, 2004). During the data collection the nurse or care provider determines whether someone has limitations in bathing himself. In other words has the patient the ability to bathe his or hers own body (Bulecheck et al, 2008). The nurse and/ or care provider collects data on (Sesink et al., 2006):
  • The habits of the client.
  • The limitations of the client.
  • Whether assistive devices are used when bathing.
  • Whether there are sensory limitations.
  • Whether the client is fearful, depressed or severely tired. In particular the effect they have on the physical hygiene.
After collecting the data the nurse / care provider as insight in (Sesink et al., 2006):
  • The degree in which a client can bathe himself.
  • Whether the client needs help of others and assistive devices.
  • The assistive devices that are needed for the care providing.
  • The help, assistance and instruction the client needs of others.
  • Whether the client needs full help.
The bathing consists of (Moorhead et al., 2008):
  • Actions that concern the conditions, like collecting the necessary items for bathing, going to the bathroom, obtaining water, controlling the temperature of the water etc.
  • Actions that concern the bathing itself, like the bathing of the face, chest, back, arms, belly, legs, tail bone, wipe dry etc.
  • The method of bathing like, washing at the sink, shower, taking a bath, washing on bed, etc.

In this stage of the nursing process it specifically concerns the determination whether someone can take care of himself independently, in this DCM specifically for bathing. During the collection of data it is observed and / or asked to the client or his immediate whether the client is able to take care of himself. If this is not the case it should be inquired what it is that the client is unable to do by himself. Then it can be inquired which aid or support the client is already receiving and by whom. This can be done by the partner or another informal care provider but also someone form a home care facility. It can also be asked whether and which assistive devices are used. For the planning of the support it is important to know which habits the client has concerning the bathing.

The results obtained by the data collection form a snapshot. During the care providing there needs to be a regular evaluation to determine the degree of independence of the client, whether he has a limitation, is unable to or has a self care deficit concerning the bathing of himself.

The nurses data collection is the first phase in the nursing process (IHE PPOC, 2009; CBO, 1999) in which the data is collected concerning the ability and the possible limitations of the client to bathe himself. The data leads to the determination of the nursing diagnosis. The diagnosis is the basis of the planning of the nursing care. In case the client is independent there will be no planning of care for bathing. In case there is a need for support and/or assistance goals, interventions and outcomes will be recorded in a care plan1. In the planning of nursing care the it is set what the final desired situation for the client ( care goals or expected outcomes) will be. The care plan is drawn to reach the goals / expected outcomes. When during an evaluation of care the conclusion is made that the goals were not reached, the first phase of the nursing process can start again (cyclical process). In case of a limitation or if the client is unable to bathe himself most often other limitations or problems are also present. Examples are: care for eyes, ears, nails, hairs, mouth, genitals, dressing and undressing and grooming like shaving, makeup, way of supporting like NDT or mobility2. ------------------------- 1 This also means care life plan, life plan, individual care plan or care plan. 2 These are examples, not a full list .

The choice whether speaking of self care, self-help or limitations is up to the nurses or care providers themselves. Often this has to do with the vision and policy of the care facility. The consistent use of these terms throughout the care process in an individual facility is the responsibility of the facility itself.

In that case, we as developers appreciate it if we were to be informed. For the coding the use of terminologies like SNOMED CT and/or LOINC, or one of the classifications of the WHO family of classifications (for example ICD10, ICF, ICNP) has been preferred. The codes that are used are, by our opinion the best possible match between the data item (variable and/or value)and the concept/ concepts as set out in the terminology or classification. It is possible that a very rigorous analysis of one of these terminologies variations emerge that are just as good or even a better match, for instance if another perspective is chosen. There is a small chance that in the future codes for certain data items are being altered. Where we did not find a code, for now, Results 4 Care codes where made and missing concepts will be asked to SNOMED CT.
